3. MANDATORY OBLIGATIONS AND RECIPROCITY

The Licensee's exercise of the rights granted in Section 2 is EXPRESSLY 
CONDITIONAL upon the fulfillment of the following obligations:

3.1. Preservation of Notices

You must retain, in the Source Form of any Derivative Works that You 
distribute, all copyright, patent, trademark, and attribution notices from the 
Source Form of the Program, excluding those notices that do not pertain to any 
part of the Derivative Works. You must cause any modified files to carry 
prominent notices stating that You changed the files and the date of any 
change.

In the Object Form of any Derivative Works that You distribute, You must 
reproduce all applicable copyright, patent, trademark, and attribution notices 
in:
    (a) the documentation and/or other materials provided with the 
        distribution, and
    (b) a "NOTICE" text file distributed as part of the Derivative Works, 
        within the Source Form or documentation, if provided along with the 
        Derivative Works.

3.2. Explicit Attribution and Change Documentation

You SHALL provide appropriate, prominent, and conspicuous credit to the 
Licensor (KordKat Lab) and all Contributors, and You SHALL:
    (a) Include a reference to this KordKat Reciprocal Attribution License 
        (KRAL) Version 1.0, with a link to the official license text if 
        distributed electronically;
    (b) Clearly and explicitly indicate if and what changes were made to the 
        original Program, distinguishing Your modifications from the original 
        work;
    (c) Ensure that such attribution is readily visible to users of the 
        Derivative Work:
        (i)  in any documentation or README files accompanying the Derivative 
             Work;
        (ii) in the user interface or "About" section if the software provides 
             such an interface;
        (iii) in any promotional or descriptive materials related to the 
              Derivative Work.

You must not remove or alter any attribution notices, copyright statements, or 
license references present in the Program. You must not misrepresent modified 
versions as being the original Program.

3.3. Reciprocal Licensing Mandate (Copyleft Provision)

If You Distribute or otherwise make publicly available the Program or any 
Derivative Work based upon the Program, THE ENTIRE WORK MUST BE LICENSED AS A 
WHOLE under the terms of this specific KordKat Reciprocal Attribution License 
(KRAL) Version 1.0 (or, at Your option, any later version officially published 
by KordKat Lab).

This reciprocal licensing requirement means:
    (a) You may NOT apply any other license terms to the Derivative Work;
    (b) You may NOT apply any additional restrictions, whether through legal 
        terms or technological measures (including but not limited to 
        encryption, obfuscation, or digital rights management), that prevent 
        recipients from exercising the rights granted by this License;
    (c) The complete work, including all components and modifications, must be 
        made available under this License;
    (d) You must include a complete copy of this License with every 
        distribution of the Program or Derivative Works.

The reciprocal nature of this License ensures that all improvements, 
modifications, and derivative works remain freely available to the entire 
community under the same terms.

3.4. Providing Source Code

Any Distribution of the Program or Derivative Works in Object Form MUST be 
accompanied by:
    (a) A complete, corresponding machine-readable copy of the Source Code, 
        distributed under the terms of this License; OR
    (b) A written offer, valid for at least three (3) years from the date of 
        Distribution and valid for as long as You offer spare parts or customer 
        support for that product model, to provide any third party, for a 
        charge no more than Your cost of physically performing source 
        distribution, a complete machine-readable copy of the corresponding 
        Source Code on a durable physical medium customarily used for software 
        interchange; OR
    (c) If distributed electronically, a prominent and clearly accessible 
        location (such as a publicly accessible version control repository) 
        from which the complete Source Code can be obtained at no charge.

The Source Code must include all the source files, build scripts, installation 
scripts, interface definition files, and any other materials necessary to 
generate, install, and (for an executable work) run the Object Code and to 
modify the Program.

3.5. Notice Requirements for Modified Versions

If You create a Derivative Work, You must:
    (a) Cause the modified files to carry prominent notices stating that You 
        changed the files and the date of any change;
    (b) Maintain a changelog or modification log documenting the nature of 
